4","1155":"1155","1229":"1229","Ermington, Devon, England":"Ermington, Devon, England","Bristol, Gloucestershire, England":"Bristol, Gloucestershire, England","Devonshire, England":"Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Newton-Peverell, Wimborne, Dorset, England":"Newton, Dorset, England"},"en":{"1172–":"1172–Deceased","1172–Male":"1172–Deceased","1172–1244":"1172–1244","1190–1237":"1190–1237","1198–1223":"1198–1223","1205–1273":"1205–1273","1146–1229":"1146–1229","1155–1230":"1155–1230","1190":"1190","about 1190":"about 1190","1198":"1198","1230":"1230","1273":"1273","1172":"1172","1290":"1290","1205":"1205","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1237":"1237","1224":"1224","1146":"1146","1223":"1223","1244":"1244","1155":"1155","1229":"1229","Ermington, Devon, England":"Ermington, Devon, England","Bristol, Gloucestershire, England":"Bristol, Gloucestershire, England","Devonshire, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Newton-Peverell, Wimborne, Dorset, England":"Newton, Dorset, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Peverell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Peverall  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Peverall","meanings":["Norman, English: relationship name from Old French  <i>Peurel</i> (Latin  <i>Piperellus</i>), a diminutive of Old French  <i>pevre</i> ‘pepper’ (Anglo-Norman French  <i>peivere</i>, Latin  <i>piper</i>), originally perhaps used as a nickname on the Continent but used as a personal name in Anglo-Norman England."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":43,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":52,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":87,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Pari